title: TTO Masterclass HAVO/VWO: 'English Heritage'
description: A complete lesson that introduces several of the countries that has British heritage, and played key role in the development of worldwide politics. Countries discussed will be England (london), Scotland (Edinburgh), Ireland (Dublin), Australia (Canberra), U.S.A. (Washington D.C.), Canada (Ottawa). The topics discussed will be: environment, culture, politics and history. Topics will be discussed globally and not necessarily in-depth. At the end of each chapter are some practice questions, and at the end is a general knowledge quiz, to see how much students are able to recall.

This digital lesson will be about several countries of the English-speaking world.

The lesson contains several short practice exercises and one general knowledge quiz at the end of the lesson.

Before we get started, it's good to evaluate what we already know about some of these countries, so we can see what we have yet to learn.

items.content:
...around the world, and we'll be visiting several English-speaking countries.

The goal of our trip is to learn as much about each country as possible, so we might pass as a native-citizen.

Each country has some strange things, some different things, and some things that are exactly the same as at home. We'll be discussing these differences together, and at the end of each class we'll be taking a short practice test.

At the end of our trip, when we get back home, we'll be taking a final test to see how much we've learned about our trip.

But for now, we'll be heading to our first location: Hop on board and let's set sail for the capital city of England!

As we sail across our little pond: The North Sea, we arrive approximately seven hours later at a large island known to us as the U.K.

But exactly what is the U.K. and how did it come to be?

The Union Jack, also known as the Union flag, is the U.K. flag though ever-changing. The first Union Jack was the flag in which both the flag of England and Scotland were forged together in 1606. The reason for this union of flags without union of states is due to the fact that James the sixth (Scottish lineage), also known as James the first (English lineage) was both king of Scotland (1567) and king of England (1603).

Son of Mary, queen of Scots gave him the throne to Scotland. Being great-great-grandson of king Henry the seventh, king of England and lord of Ireland, gave him acces to the throne of both England and Ireland. Establishing him to be the O.G. triple threat.

James did become king of all three kingdoms, and fancied himself "King of Great Britain and Ireland". The Scottish proclaimed him as "James the sixth, king of Scotland" though he was later proclaimed by the English as "James the first, king of Great Britain, France and Ireland, defender of the faith".

It is noteworthy that James was in fact not the king of France, this proclamation is simply based on an unending tug of war between France and England, and is more meant as a taunt towards France from England. The proclamation "defender of faith" started back in 1507 and was given to king Henry the eighth (the man with six wives who we'll learn more about in England) when he married Catherine of Aragon (huge catholic) in 1521 by pope Leo the tenth. This has to do with the division of the church way back in 1053. In short, anyone willing to acknowledge the catholic pope to reign supreme in the Christian faith will be rewarded with the title "defender of faith" in exchange for their loyalty.

The Union Jack however, like mentioned before, is ever-changing. As in 1801 it also contained the Saint Patrick's cross flag, which was and still is NOT the flag of Ireland. The flag of Ireland used to be a blue/green flag with a golden harp on it and was replaced by the Union Jack in 1801, also known as the U.K. flag we can see now. In 1919 the Irish flag was a green flag with the words "Irish Republic" on it. In 1922 Ireland got its final flag design, the one it still flies till this day: vertical stripes green, white, and orange. The reason behind these changing flag has to do with the politics in Ireland and their struggle with independence from England on which we will learn more when we get to Ireland.

The U.K., short for the United Kingdom was established in 1706 when England and Scotland formed a political union in which bloodshed didn't fall short. This unitary state was also known as Great Britain or The Kingdom of Great Britain.

Wales was included in the Kingdom of England back in the day when the U.K. was first established.

Almost a century later, on August 1st 1800 Ireland joined the U.K. on which it took many steps in the coming decades to declare independence and establish 'home rule'.

We'll be learning more about these troubling times when we get Ireland, but right now we're setting foot in the capital city of the U.K., which also happens to be the capital of England: London.

items.caption: So what exactly is the U.K.?

items.content:
London

As we step foot in London, we first head over to some of its most famous locations.

Starting with parliament square:

One of its most famous sights being "The Big Ben", but in fact contrary to belief its real name is the "Elisabeth Clock Tower". It's actually the bell inside the clock tower that is nicknamed ¨Big Ben". The name "Big Ben" comes from Benjamin Hall, he was quite a big guy and the man who pushed for the building of the tower. And so, "Big Ben" came about.

Another familiar sight is the Wesminster Abbey. This is the church where crownings, funerals, and marriages of the royal family of England take place. The church has a gothic architecture and was established somewhere mid 11th century.

On the square we can also see a statue of lord Winston Churchill, a famous figure known for his writing as well as his political career. Of course most famous for being prime minister in 1940-1945 and again from 1951-1955. Known for leading the U.K. to victory during WWII.

Of course the reason for the name "parliament square" is due to the House of Parliament, which is the informal name for the Palace of Westminster. It is the meeting place for "The House of Commons" and "The House of Lords". Which is like our Dutch first and second room, or "eerste en tweede kamer".
